  <h2>1. The "one-word reply" escalation</h2>
  <p>One person spirals; the other answers in single words. The gap is the joke.</p>
  <pre><code>Me: So I may have done something today
Me: Don't be mad
Me: It was on sale though
Me: And technically we needed a new one
Mom: What
Me: I bought a boat
Mom: k</code></pre>

  <h2>2. The wrong-number plot twist</h2>
  <p>Starts as a mistake, turns into a whole story. Great for cliffhangers.</p>
  <pre><code>Unknown: Hey it's Jake from the party, you gave me this number
Me: I think you have the wrong number
Unknown: Wait is this not Sarah?
Me: Nope
Unknown: ...this is so embarrassing
Unknown: ok but since you're here, what's your opinion on pineapple pizza</code></pre>

  <h2>3. The delusional confidence</h2>
  <p>Someone massively overestimates the situation. The punchline is the reality check.</p>
  <pre><code>Me: I think she's into me
Me: She waved at me today
Ryan: She waved back because YOU waved first
Me: Details
Ryan: You've never spoken
Me: We have a connection</code></pre>

  <h2>4. The read-receipt heartbreak</h2>
  <p>Left on read is universal comedy (and tragedy). The timestamp does the work.</p>
  <pre><code>Me: Hey! Was great meeting you last night 😊
Me: We should grab coffee sometime
Me: Or not, no pressure lol
Me: Anyway have a good week!
Me: cool</code></pre>

